{"type":"system","subtype":"init","cwd":"/home/aviadr1/projects/kaizen-autoresearch/experiments/write-test-plan","session_id":"bd7962cf-c1ac-44fa-946c-fb8b49a89979","tools":["StructuredOutput","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__analyze_issue_with_seer","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__create_dsn","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__create_project","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__create_team","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__find_dsns","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__find_organizations","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__find_projects","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__find_releases","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__find_teams","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__get_doc","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__get_event_attachment","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__get_issue_tag_values","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__get_profile_details","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__get_sentry_resource","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__search_docs","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__search_events","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__search_issue_events","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__search_issues","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__update_issue","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__update_project","mcp__claude_ai_Sentry__whoami"],"mcp_servers":[{"name":"claude.ai Gmail","status":"needs-auth"},{"name":"claude.ai Sentry","status":"connected"},{"name":"claude.ai Linear","status":"failed"},{"name":"claude.ai Figma","status":"needs-auth"}],"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","permissionMode":"default","slash_commands":["update-config","debug","simplify","batch","loop","schedule","claude-api","write-prd","post-run-report","run-experiment","mine-ideas","slack:draft-announcement","slack:standup","slack:find-discussions","slack:channel-digest","slack:summarize-channel","slack:slack-search","slack:slack-messaging","compact","context","cost","heapdump","init","pr-comments","release-notes","review","security-review","extra-usage","insights"],"apiKeySource":"none","claude_code_version":"2.1.86","output_style":"default","agents":["general-purpose","statusline-setup","Explore","Plan","claude-code-guide"],"skills":["update-config","debug","simplify","batch","loop","schedule","claude-api","slack:slack-search","slack:slack-messaging"],"plugins":[{"name":"slack","path":"/home/aviadr1/.claude/plugins/cache/claude-plugins-official/slack/1.0.0","source":"slack@claude-plugins-official"}],"uuid":"73669e6f-397f-4481-bec1-1b57b0ac3c08","fast_mode_state":"off"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_011KKm56H7qS22dteH5ZPyYQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is a test plan writing task for a patient intake system. Let me work through each behavior systematically, asking the key questions to determine the appropriate test level.\n\nThe system has these key components:\n- Patient data validation\n- Insurance eligibility API call (external payer API)\n- AI symptom triage (LLM-based urgency assessment)\n- Scheduling (writes to shared calendar DB)\n- Confirmation message\n\nLet me go through each behavior:\n\n**Behavior 1: Required patient fields validation**\n- Missing fields produce a clear error listing all missing items\n- Key questions:\n  - MOCK-MISS: Could a mock miss this? No — field validation is purely in-process logic\n  - REAL-INFRA: Does it need OS, network, subprocess? No\n  - MOCK-HIDE: Would mocking hide failure? No — it's straightforward input validation\n  - LLM-DEP: Does it depend on LLM? No\n  - MULTI-STEP: Is it multi-step agentic? No\n- This is pure function behavior: validate(patient_data) → error message\n- **Minimum level: Unit** — one function, no I/O, no dependencies\n- Confidence: Unit 0.95, Integration 0.05, System 0.0, Agentic 0.0, Workflow 0.0\n\n**Behavior 2: Date of birth validation**\n- Rejects future dates, dates >150 years ago, non-date strings\n- Key questions:\n  - MOCK-MISS: Could a mock miss this? No — it's pure date validation logic\n  - REAL-INFRA: Need real OS/network? No\n  - MOCK-HIDE: Would mocking hide it? No\n  - LLM-DEP: LLM involved? No\n  - MULTI-STEP: Multi-step agentic? No\n- This is a pure validation function\n\n\n- **Minimum level: Unit** — isolated date validation function\n- Confidence: Unit 0.95, Integration 0.05, System 0.0, Agentic 0.0, Workflow 0.0\n\n**Behavior 3: Insurance eligibility check**\n- Sends correct patient ID and plan code to payer API\n- Correctly interprets \"eligible\" vs \"not eligible\" vs \"pending\" response\n- Key questions:\n  - MOCK-MISS: Could a mock miss this? YES — a mock API will always return what you tell it to. But the key failure here is: does the code correctly construct the request and parse the response? The \"sending correct data\" part could be missed by a mock that doesn't validate the request payload. A real API call would reject malformed requests, exposing bugs in request construction. The response parsing logic could also be wrong — a mock might return the exact format expected, hiding parsing failures.\n  - REAL-INFRA: Need real OS/network? YES — this is an external API call\n  - MOCK-HIDE: Would mocking hide it? YES — request construction and response parsing bugs could be masked\n  - LLM-DEP: LLM involved? No\n  - MULTI-STEP: Multi-step agentic? No\n- This requires integration testing with a real or realistic API to catch request/response bugs that mocks would hide.\n- **Minimum level: Integration** — external API dependency, request/response validation\n- Confidence: Unit 0.1, Integration 0.85, System 0.05, Agentic 0.0, Workflow 0.0 catch real failures in request construction and response parsing. A validating mock could expose wrong field names or incorrect interpretation logic, but to truly verify the contract between our system and the payer API, an integration test is more reliable. The minimum level needed is integration testing—multiple components working together to validate the request/response contract. Unit testing alone risks hiding failures that only surface when the actual API interaction occurs. A mock that doesn't validate the actual API contract could easily miss failures—if our expectations don't match what the real API returns, we won't catch it until later. Integration testing becomes necessary to verify the actual request and response formats align with our code. While a well-designed unit test with contract validation could catch some issues like incorrect field names or parsing logic, the risk of mocking incorrectly is too high for APIs. I'd argue integration testing is the minimum needed here, ideally using a test double like WireMock that enforces the real contract. The core issue is that unit tests can only validate against our assumptions about the API, not the API itself.\n\nFor the unreachable payer API scenario, the system should mark eligibility as pending and continue processing. The question becomes whether a mock would catch this behavior—and that depends on whether we've explicitly mocked the failure case.\n\nA mock that always succeeds would hide the actual error handling path. Testing network resilience requires either simulating the failure in a mock (by raising an exception) or hitting a real network call. The core concern is graceful degradation when the external service is unavailable. While a unit test with an exception-throwing mock could validate the error logic, integration testing better confirms the system actually handles the failure end-to-end. **Integration is the minimum level needed** to verify this behavior, though a well-designed unit test with proper exception mocking could work if the error handling is purely synchronous logic. system intake continues without crashing, and you're validating the entire resilience pattern under realistic conditions rather than just the exception-handling logic in isolation.\n\nFor the AI symptom triage behavior, the core issue is that a mock LLM can't validate the actual classification logic. A mock will always return whatever you program it to return, so it won't catch cases where the real model misclassifies dangerous symptom combinations. Since the correctness fundamentally depends on the actual LLM's output, this requires a real model or at minimum a test against actual model behavior to ensure high-urgency conditions like chest pain with shortness of breath are properly flagged.\n\nThe natural language explanation behavior has a similar constraint—a mock could return any text string and the test would pass without checking whether the explanation is actually clinically useful. The quality of the explanation is entirely dependent on the real LLM's generation capability, so you need to test against the actual model to verify clinicians would find the output meaningful and accurate.\n\nFor appointment scheduling, the situation changes. A mock database can be configured to return whatever you want, which means it won't catch real failures like incorrect availability checking or improper filtering by urgency windows. The actual code might pick the wrong slot or fail to respect time constraints, but a mock would always have slots available. Testing against a real calendar system with actual time constraints is necessary to verify the scheduling logic works correctly—this requires Integration level testing.\n\nConcurrent booking introduces a different problem. Mocks handle concurrency differently than actual databases do, and a mock without proper locking could pass when the real system fails due to race conditions. You need a real database with concurrent connections to verify transactional behavior and ensure the system prevents double-booking when multiple patients are processed simultaneously. This pushes the requirement to System or Integration level testing, depending on whether you use a real test database with proper transaction handling.\n\nThe key distinction: Integration testing with a containerized test database (PostgreSQL with transactions, for example) would catch these issues without needing production infrastructure. System testing against the actual production configuration would be overkill. So Integration becomes the minimum viable level—you need real database behavior, but not necessarily the production environment itself.\n\n---\n\nFor the confirmation message behavior, the core requirement is that it includes specific fields: patient name, appointment time, provider name, and preparation instructions. This is fundamentally a templating problem. A unit test can verify the message contains all required fields without any external infrastructure. The behavior statement focuses on what the message includes, not whether it gets delivered, so I/O testing isn't necessary at the minimum level. Unit testing suffices here—just validate the message structure and content.\n\nThe full intake pipeline is fundamentally different. It chains together validation, insurance checks, symptom triage, scheduling, and confirmation across multiple services. The LLM dependency for symptom triage means behavior depends on AI reasoning, not just deterministic logic. Real infrastructure is required because the pipeline orchestrates actual services rather than isolated components. Mocking individual services could mask integration failures where the pipeline breaks down between steps. This is inherently multi-step agentic work that demands integration testing to verify the entire flow completes successfully for a real patient submission. probability distribution across the five levels for each behavior, where the values sum to 1.0. This represents my confidence that each level is the minimum required to catch a real failure.\n\nFor field validation, I'm highly confident a unit test suffices—95% chance it's the minimum level needed. There's a small 5% possibility some integration aspect could affect validation that I'm not seeing. For DOB validation, the reasoning is similar: unit tests should catch it reliably, with minimal chance it requires a higher level. For the insurance API check, I need to think through whether unit mocking is sufficient or if integration testing becomes necessary. For the Insurance API behavior, a well-designed unit test with mocking could catch request/response issues, though I'm only 60% confident that's sufficient—there's a 40% chance I'd need integration testing to verify the actual API contract. For the unreachable API scenario, mocking an exception in a unit test might work (40% confidence), but I'm more confident that integration testing is necessary to properly exercise the full flow when the API is down (60% confidence).\n\nWhen it comes to AI-driven symptom triage, unit tests with mocked LLM responses would miss the actual classification behavior—I'm only 5% confident that's enough. Integration testing with cached responses could help slightly (10% confidence), but the real issue is that I need agentic-level testing to validate realistic LLM behavior (80% confidence). Similarly, for natural language explanations, mocking would produce meaningless text (5% confidence), cached responses in integration testing might partially work (10% confidence), and real LLM API calls through system testing could be viable.\n\nFor appointment scheduling, I can mock the database at the unit level, though that skips real availability logic (30% confidence). Integration testing with an actual database is where the scheduling logic truly gets validated (70% confidence). Concurrency and double-booking prevention specifically requires a real test database with transaction support—unit mocks won't catch race conditions (5% confident they would), making integration testing essential (85% confident), with a small chance system-level testing is needed for production configuration (10% confidence). Confirmation messages appear to be testable at the unit level.\n\nFor the confirmation message behavior, I'm testing just the message content itself (85% confident that's unit-level), though integration testing only matters if message delivery is part of the requirement (15% confident). The full pipeline—validation, insurance checks, symptom triage via LLM, scheduling, and confirmation—involves multiple layers. Unit testing alone won't work given the real dependencies (5% confident), and while mocking the LLM could make integration testing viable (15% confident), the agentic step with the actual LLM is the critical piece (60% confident), especially since multiple agentic steps run in sequence (5% confident that workflow-level testing applies).\n\nThe real question is what catches actual failures across the entire flow. Validation errors, unreachable APIs, incorrect LLM outputs, database failures, malformed messages, and incomplete sequences all represent different failure modes. Unit tests miss integration issues, mocked integration tests miss LLM failures, and a single agentic test doesn't verify the full sequence working together. Only a workflow test with all real dependencies running end-to-end would catch everything. The question hinges on what counts as a \"real failure.\" Integration tests catch API timeouts and database issues, agentic tests verify the LLM produces correct triage decisions, and workflow tests validate the entire sequence with all dependencies working together. Since the behavior explicitly requires the full pipeline to complete end-to-end for a real patient, I need a test level that exercises all components—LLM, database, APIs, and the orchestration between them. Workflow testing is the only approach that captures this comprehensively, though it's worth noting that agentic testing alone would miss integration failures and integration testing alone would miss LLM failures. we test the full sequence once with real data, that would catch most failures. But that's essentially a Workflow test since the distinction is whether we're testing a single agentic step versus multiple steps in sequence. The intake pipeline has multiple dependencies—validate, API call, LLM triage, database scheduling, message generation—so a single Agentic test wouldn't be sufficient. An Integration test with a mocked LLM would miss the actual model's behavior and unpredictability. I'm settling on Workflow as the minimum viable test level, though there's some uncertainty about whether Agentic could work if it covered the full sequence. My confidence: Workflow=0.70, Agentic=0.20, System=0.10.\n\nThe real failure modes I need to catch are the LLM producing incorrect triage, API calls failing, database writes failing, and steps not connecting properly. To surface all of these, I need both the real LLM behavior and the actual external system interactions. Workflow is the right fit because it's explicitly designed for testing multiple real dependencies and full agent pipelines, not just isolated agentic steps.\n\nMy final assessment: Workflow=0.75, Agentic=0.20, System=0.05, Integration=0.0, Unit=0.0\n\nNow I need to document each behavior with test descriptions and verify the plan is internally consistent across all ten behaviors.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6670,"cache_read_input_tokens":21466,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6670},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bd7962cf-c1ac-44fa-946c-fb8b49a89979","uuid":"af4bd26c-3c36-4e5d-bb5b-6c30d1ba6619"}
